reviewText: This course is a waste of time and money. You might as well just go read the PMBOK. I had to put the instructors at 2x speed just to get through the lectures. The quizzes ask basic questions that are all just small differences in syntax and terminology. The case study template they give you doesn't allow for any flexibility, and the case study itself is irrelevant to anything I'll be doing. Probably a better course for construction management. Not applicable to engineers who don't work with clients on every project.

Course is good. However, certificate issued is mentioned as '...online non-credit course...' create confusion. Such words should not be included in certificate, rather such info (credit, non-credit etc.) should be on back-end. Just issue simple certificate that online course including assignments and exam is successfully completed by Mr. X which is offered by RICE University USA on Coursera. It does not make any sense to write that the course is credit, non-credit etc. I am not happy with certificate issued.
N/A

The proposed template has different fields from the rubric, so basically it's not a template.Don't follow it if you want to pass the assignment because if don't, there will not be anyone to correct your assignment again.
The assessors are other students on the course. The course material is okay but its value is diminished by this reviewing process. Some students actually offer to swap 100% scores on the forums.

30 years running programs, up to five years @ $3M/yr. Only four units in I want to fire somebody. Material correlates very poorly with quizzes... about half the answers can not be found directly in the PMBOK or presentations. The assignments are a total load... info provided is completely insufficient to do the work. Cumulative and iterative building of project docs is difficult since the expectations for each type of assignment do not "nest" properly. For example, a 1120 hour project has 28+ items on the WBS. Now they want this resolved into a CPM diagram? Effort hours info is in nine categories, which are not well-correlated to anything and thus need to be spread laterally across functions. And still add up. Without software this is an all-day job, notwithstanding that it requires some judgement beyond scope of the class.
Peer reviews are quite subjective, the peers often do not stick to the rubric. I wish more tests or assignments graded by professionals.
